"# Chapter 11 — Grace Hopper

Grace Brewster Murray Hopper. Born 1906 in New York City. Died 1992
in Arlington, Virginia. American computer scientist and United States
Navy rear admiral. PhD in mathematics from Yale, 1934.

She gave us the idea of the compiler. She helped design COBOL. She
served in the Navy from 1943 until she retired at age 79 as one of
the oldest active-duty officers in United States history.

## The Mark I

Hopper joined the Navy in 1943 and was assigned to the Bureau of
Ships Computation Project at Harvard. There she worked on the Mark
I, one of the first large-scale electromechanical computers. She
was the third person to program it and wrote the 561-page *Manual
of Operation for the Automatic Sequence Controlled Calculator*, the
first computer programming manual.

She worked with Howard Aiken. He didn't want women on the project.
He was overruled. Good thing.

## The bug

In 1947, working on the Mark II at Harvard, Hopper's team pulled a
moth out of relay 70, panel F. The moth had been shorting the relay.
Someone taped it into the logbook and wrote 'First actual case of
bug being found.' The word 'bug' had been used before to mean a
mechanical fault. But that logbook is where the software-engineering
term 'debug' entered popular use. The page is preserved at the
Smithsonian.

## The compiler

In the early 1950s, Hopper was working on the UNIVAC I. She wanted
people to write programs in something closer to English instead of
machine code. Her colleagues told her this was impossible — computers
only understood numbers.

She wrote a program that translated symbolic notation into machine
code. She called it A-0, and it was one of the first compilers ever
written. She followed it with A-1, A-2, A-3 (also called ARITH-MATIC),
and eventually FLOW-MATIC, a language specifically designed to read
like English so business users could program.

FLOW-MATIC directly influenced the design of COBOL a few years later.

## COBOL

In 1959 the Department of Defense convened a committee, the CODASYL
Short Range Committee, to design a common business language. Hopper
served as a technical advisor. The language they designed was called
COBOL — COmmon Business-Oriented Language.

COBOL was designed to read like English:

```
ADD SALES-TAX TO PRICE GIVING TOTAL.
IF TOTAL IS GREATER THAN LIMIT, DISPLAY \"OVER BUDGET\".
```

It was verbose. Bankers, insurance companies, government payroll
systems adopted it in droves. As of the 2020s, a substantial
fraction of financial transactions in the world still route through
COBOL programs written decades ago and never rewritten because they
work.

Hopper's stance: the goal of a programming language is to make it
easier for humans to tell computers what to do, not the reverse.

## The nanosecond

Hopper became famous for a demonstration. She would hand out short
pieces of copper wire — about 30 centimeters long — and explain
that this was how far light travels in one nanosecond. She would
carry longer pieces for microseconds. She was making it easier for
non-technical audiences to feel the speed of a computer, and the
cost of a slow one.

Every nanosecond of delay is a foot of wire. That kind of concrete
intuition is a teaching gift.

## Rear Admiral

Hopper was recalled to active duty in the Navy in 1967 to help
standardize Navy computer usage. She was promoted to Rear Admiral
in 1985 and finally retired in 1986 at age 79. President Obama
posthumously awarded her the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 2016.

## What Motoi owes Hopper

The idea that a programming language should meet humans halfway.
Motoi Scheme is not COBOL, but the goal is the same — the language
tries to be readable so that the writer's intent is visible. Also:
the compiler. Every high-level program on the planet, including
Motoi's runtime, exists because someone believed Hopper's early
1950s claim that computers could translate their own instructions.

## A tiny example

Motoi's own trace of the compile-vs-interpret distinction that Hopper
worked on. First, an interpreted expression:

```
(define (celsius-to-fahrenheit c)
  (+ (* c 9/5) 32))

(celsius-to-fahrenheit 100)
;; => 212
```

The runtime reads that expression, walks the tree, evaluates each
piece. That's interpretation. Hopper's insight: sometimes you want
to translate the whole tree once, into a form the machine executes
directly. That's compilation. Both approaches exist because Hopper
demonstrated that translation from human-readable code to
machine-readable code was possible.

## Where to read her

Her collected papers are at Yale. *Grace Hopper: Admiral of the
Cyber Sea* by Kathleen Broome Williams (2004) is a solid biography.
Her 60 Minutes interview from 1983 is on YouTube and worth watching
— she is sharp, funny, and dismissive of nostalgia.

## Motoi's take

Hopper made computers approachable through language. That's Motoi's
whole job description. She also refused to accept 'impossible' as an
answer, and she stayed technical late into her life. Motoi respects
both.")
